[2] Thailand, H5N1
Date: Thu 15 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Nation, 15 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.nationmultimedia.com/page.news.php3?clid=1&theme=A&usrsess=1&id=117316>

New bird flu outbreak: containment strategy working, Thaksin says
-----------------------------------------------
The outbreak of bird flu in 7 provinces is not another epidemic, rather, it
demonstrates quick detection of the killer virus as part of a successful
rapid-containment strategy, Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra said
yesterday [Wed 14 Jul 2004]. "The fresh outbreaks are the resurgence of
avian influenza that's been dormant since early this year [2004]," Thaksin
said.
The flare up had not grounded exports of cooked chicken meat, and, would
not spiral out of control, he said.
Government veterinarians were under strict orders to destroy suspiciously
sick chickens immediately rather than wait for lab test results.
Agriculture Minister Somsak Thepsuthin said his ministry was taking
measures to prevent wild migratory birds from infecting farm chickens.
[Earlier published intentions to kill storks have been cancelled, which
means, the prevention measures should encompass segregation of domestic
poultry. - Mod.AS].
Yukol Limlamthong, director general of the ministry's Livestock Development
Department, instructed his officials to intensify checks of poultry farms.
"Every preventive measure must be strictly enforced, and, no chicken, dying
unexplainably, should be sent to a slaughterhouse and processed, or sold,
for human consumption," he said.
Vets are expected to investigate suspected cases at farms, he said.
The ban on vaccinating fowl nationwide stays in place to avoid speeding up
mutations of the virus that could cause it to jump to people. "The poultry
industry would be ruined if bird flu were able to spread from human to
human," he said.
A decision on allowing limited vaccinations of chickens for domestic
consumption would wait until next week [3rd week July 2004]. "I have to
weigh the pros and cons of the proposal, and, will submit my report to
Deputy Prime Minister Chaturon Chaisang," he said. [Readers are referred
to FAO's relevant reference in item 4: "Targeted and strictly monitored
vaccination using a quality-assured vaccine remains a complementary
option." - Mod.AS].
Hasty immunizations by poultry breeders would result in the mandatory
culling of their chickens, he warned.
A Siriraj Hospital virologist had earlier feared that the bird flu might
have already jumped to pigs, but, the latest checks by leading virologists,
at home and abroad, found no mutation of the H5N1 strain here, he said.
About 60 non-farm chickens in Chiang Rai, and 30 in Bangkok, were quickly
disposed of yesterday [Wed 14 Jul 2004] after some were suspected to have
come down with bird flu.
--
