[3] WHO
Date: Thu 15 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance Weekly 8(29), 15 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2004/040715.asp>

Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) outbreaks, South East Asia: WHO
response
-----------------------------------------------
2 press releases, from the World Health Organization (WHO), last week [2nd
week July 2004] have refocused international attention on highly pathogenic
avian influenza (HPAI) A(H5N1) [1,2]. During the past 3 weeks [1st week of
June, 1st and 2nd weeks of July 2004], an outbreak of HPAI A(H5N1) has been
confirmed in Anhui province (China), and, outbreaks caused by a virus, so
far identified only as H5, have been confirmed in provinces north of
Bangkok (Thailand) and the Mekong Delta (Viet Nam). These outbreaks may be
new, or, continuations of the outbreaks reported earlier in 2004. Details
of the recent outbreaks can be seen on the web-site of the World
Organisation for Animal Health, OIE, <http://www.oie.int>
[3]). No human infections have been confirmed in these countries, and
control efforts are underway, including the culling of poultry in the
immediate vicinity of the outbreaks, vaccination of poultry within a wider
area, and limiting the movement of people living in the affected areas.
The WHO also calls attention to 2 research reports, published this month
[July 2004], which add to the understanding of the virus. The 1st indicates
that the virus may be widespread in domestic ducks in southern China, and,
that it has also caused increasingly severe disease in experimental mice
over the period 1999-2002 [4]. The 2nd reports that the virus may be
spreading via both domestic and wild birds, suggesting that it may be more
difficult to control than previously thought [5].
WHO is actively offering assistance -- and strongly encouraging counties to
take advantage of this offer of assistance -- with risk assessment
activities in affected countries, including enhanced surveillance of
animals and humans, and, strain analysis. The WHO is also urging these
countries' authorities to allow WHO's international reference laboratories
full access to all viral isolates and clinical specimens, so that more can
be learned about H5N1 viruses, which may differ from one another.
Although no human infections are so far confirmed, the WHO is keenly aware
that the H5N1 virus could adapt the ability to spread easily from human to
human. The WHO is working closely [with] agriculture authorities, and other
international organizations, including the OIE and the Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO). <http://www.fao.org/>
Pandemic preparedness activities, and pandemic vaccine development, continue.
References:
WHO Communicable Disease Surveillance & Response. Avian influenza -
Current evaluation of risks to humans from H5N1 following recent reports.
Disease Outbreak News, 8 Jul 2004. <http://www.who.int/csr/don/2004_07_08/en/>
WHO Western Pacific Region. WHO urges prompt action on avian
influenza outbreaks. Press release, 9 Jul 2004.
<http://www.wpro.who.int/public/press_release/press_view.asp?id=406>
OIE. Update on avian influenza in animals in Asia (Type H5). 13 Jul 2004.
<http://www.oie.int/downld/AVIAN%20INFLUENZA/A_AI-Asia.htm> [accessed 15
July 2004]
Chen H, Deng G, Li Z, Tian G, Li Y, Jiao P, et al. The evolution of H5N1
influenza viruses in ducks in southern China. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S
A 2004; 101(28): 10452-7. Published online before print 2 Jul 2004,
10.1073/pnas.0403212101.
<http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/101/28/10452>
Li KS, Guan Y, Wang J, Smith GJD, Xu KM, Duan L, et al.. Genesis of a
highly pathogenic and potentially pandemic H5N1 influenza virus in eastern
Asia. Nature 2004; 430: 209-13.
